    <text id="R12210092T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>General Henry Wise commanded a Confederate brigade during the summer, 1861,
                    struggle for what is now West Virginia. Staunton served as a base of supply in
                    these actions as evidenced by General William Wing Loring's letter announcing
                    the movement by rail of reinforcements through Staunton.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    HEADQUARTERS NORTHWEST ARMY,
                    <name type="recipient">Col. GEORGE DEAS, Adjutant-Gen.:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1861-07-30">July 30, 1861.</date>
                        <name type="place">Huntersville, Va.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>COLONEL:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have just seen a reliable man who tells me that he was in Gen. Wise's camp las
                    Friday, 26th July; that Wise was at Gauey Brigade, on his retreat to Lewisburg,
                    about sixty miles distant. He thinks that Wise intended to fight the enemy at
                    Tompkins' [farm], eight miles from the bridge.</p>
                <p>Upon learning this, I sent word to Staunton for the two Georgia regiments and the
                    battery expected at Staunton to be moved by the train to Millsborough, there to
                    remain until further orders.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Respectfully, your obedient servant,</salute>
                    <signed>W. W. LORING,<lb/> Brig.-Gen., Commanding.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
